# Nil Python holds and passes a raw C pointer (handle) with no wrapper unit:
# malloc returns void*, the local `p` is inferred as a pointer from the callee
# return, and it is passed straight back to free. This is the handle mechanic
# the wrapper-free nilpy<->C arc builds on — a .npy program can carry an opaque
# C handle across calls. (Out-param `&` and char*->string marshalling are the
# remaining pieces; see the handover.)
import stdlib
p = malloc(64)
free(p)
print(1)
